---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "VTU, MAKAUT, CBSE, DU Conversion Formulas Explained";
const description =
    "Learn the official and widely used grade conversion formulas for VTU, MAKAUT, CBSE, DU, and other universities. Convert SGPA, CGPA, YGPA, and GPA to percentage accurately.";
const keywords =
    "VTU CGPA to Percentage, MAKAUT CGPA conversion, CBSE CGPA to percentage, DU CGPA equivalent, university grade conversion formulas";
const pageUrl = "https://personal-projects-djf.pages.dev/formulas";
const socialImage = "https://personal-projects-djf.pages.dev/og-image.jpg";
---

<Layout {title} {description} {keywords} {pageUrl} {socialImage}>
    <div class="w-full max-w-3xl mx-auto py-12 px-4 md:py-16 md:px-6">
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-(--c3) mb-6">
            University Conversion Formulas Explained
        </h1>

        <p class="text-(--c4) opacity-80 leading-relaxed mb-8">
            Many Indian universities follow different formulas to convert SGPA,
            CGPA, or YGPA into percentages. This guide explains the commonly
            used and officially recommended methods for VTU, MAKAUT, CBSE, DU,
            and others.
        </p>

        <div
            class="bg-(--c2)/40 backdrop-blur border border-(--c3)/20 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 space-y-10 text-(--c4)"
        >
            <!-- VTU -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-(--c3) mb-3">
                    1. VTU (Visvesvaraya Technological University)
                </h2>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    VTU uses an official formula to convert CGPA or SGPA to
                    percentage:
                </p>
                <div
                    class="p-4 bg-(--c2)/50 border border-(--c3)/20 rounded-xl mb-4"
                >
                    <p class="font-semibold text-(--c3)">
                        Percentage = (CGPA - 0.75) x 10
                    </p>
                </div>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed">
                    This formula is widely accepted for academic and placement
                    purposes.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- MAKAUT -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-(--c3) mb-3">
                    2. MAKAUT (Formerly WBUT)
                </h2>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    MAKAUT uses YGPA/CGPA-based conversion according to their
                    official notifications:
                </p>

                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 opacity-90 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>CGPA ≥ 9.0</strong> → 90% and above</li>
                    <li><strong>CGPA 8.0 - 8.9</strong> → 80% - 89%</li>
                    <li><strong>CGPA 7.0 - 7.9</strong> → 70% - 79%</li>
                    <li><strong>CGPA 6.0 - 6.9</strong> → 60% - 69%</li>
                </ul>

                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mt-3">
                    MAKAUT does not use a straight mathematical formula; it uses
                    grade brackets.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- CBSE -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-(--c3) mb-3">
                    3. CBSE (Central Board of Secondary Education)
                </h2>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    CBSE's standard conversion formula for CGPA (Class 10) is:
                </p>

                <div
                    class="p-4 bg-(--c2)/50 border border-(--c3)/20 rounded-xl mb-4"
                >
                    <p class="font-semibold text-(--c3)">
                        Percentage = CGPA x 9.5
                    </p>
                </div>

                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed">
                    This formula is officially published by CBSE and used for
                    class X marksheets.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- DU -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-(--c3) mb-3">
                    4. DU (Delhi University)
                </h2>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    Delhi University has its own grade conversion system:
                </p>

                <div
                    class="p-4 bg-(--c2)/50 border border-(--c3)/20 rounded-xl mb-4"
                >
                    <p class="font-semibold text-(--c3)">
                        Percentage = CGPA x 9.5
                    </p>
                </div>

                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed">
                    For some departments, DU uses brackets similar to MAKAUT,
                    depending on the program.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- General Formula -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-(--c3) mb-3">
                    5. Common / General Formula
                </h2>
                <p class="opacity-90 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    Most universities that do not provide an official method use
                    the following widely accepted formula:
                </p>

                <div
                    class="p-4 bg-(--c2)/50 border border-(--c3)/20 rounded-xl"
                >
                    <p class="font-semibold text-(--c3)">
                        Percentage = CGPA x 10
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>